README DoodleJump

Overview:

    Our DoodleJump program mimics the real "DoodleJump" game as designed by Lima Sky. We tried to recreate the
    authentic version of DoodleJump with a squared-paper background, exact coloring of platforms, and the score
    increments. We hope you enjoy the added features like our special platforms and restart button!

    Our program has six classes: The App, Constants, Doodle, DoodleJump, PaneOrganizer, and Platform.

    • In the App class, we created the scene (the window) of the Balaton application. We created a start method, in
      which PaneOrganizer and Scene were instantiated. We passed in a getter method for root so all the written methods
      and shapes in the pane can be shown within a constant boundary.
    • In the Constants class, we declared the each of our constants in an organized way as type int, double,
      color or string.
    • In the Doodle shape class, we created the instance of our doodle, a golden rectangle with black outlining. We
      set its position, and detected collision with the platforms.
    • In the DoodleJump top-level logic class, we handle the timeline, key input, scrolling, intersection, spawning,
      moving and anything game mechanics including our staple, very fancy "Game Over!" text.
    • In the PaneOrganizer top-level graphical class, we created the border pane, the playerPlane, the score labels,
     the quit button, our background image, and the buttonPane.
    • In the Platform class, we handled the creation of our special platforms with their respective velocities,
     colors, types, and positions. We decided to handle the moving of the platforms in the logical class, so that
     platforms update with the timeline.

Design Choices:

    We used a switch statement to create the relation between a key press and movement movement methods. The switch
    statement will evaluate each case of an arrow key pressed, and will return the corresponding movement of the
    doodle in the playerPlane. We also used switch statements to set up the platform types after randomization.

    We used a timeline so that the game platform moving, doodle bouncing, scrolling, score, wrapping is all  .
    updated using a Lambda expression and KeyFrame that updates every 0.016 seconds.

    We used if/else statements a lot because it seemed like a better solution for logical arguments. This was so
    it would be easier to think about how the code works logically and how it convenes in graphics.

    We used for, while, and for-each loops for effective iteration of statements described in our code. This was
    FOR-EACH iterating through the platform arraylist to make them move for example. We used a WHILE loop to remove
    platforms logically after they left the playerPane for example. Lastly, we used a FOR loop to add a
    drop-shadow effect on our game over title.

    We used arraylists to store the values of the platforms. This seemed like the best design solution instead of
    declaring 6 different types of arrays in our platform class.

Known Bugs:

    There are no known bugs in our program.

Debugging Collaborators

    None.

Hours Spent:

    30 hours.

